    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-03T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-03T06:00:00-05:00" n="608"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d608">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.00B International Red Day/220: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-03T14:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 3, 1941—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 3—1:56 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>897. The press accounts of the May Day parades throughout the Soviet Union
                    emphasize the new Soviet artillery and aircraft. The usual figures of the
                    numbers of airplanes taking part in the demonstrations are omitted.
                        Timoshenko’s<note n="41" xml:id="d608fn41">Marshal Semën Konstantinovich
                        Timoshenko, People’s Commissar for Defense of the Soviet Union since May
                        1940.</note> speech in the Red Square, which is published today, emphasized
                    the desire of the Soviet Government for peace and for the improvement of its
                    relations with all nations that likewise desire better relations. Minister of
                    War called for <pb facs="0625" n="613" xml:id="pg_613"/> vigilance and the
                    continued strengthening of Soviet economic and military power.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
